Jun 14 2008 	Modern and Clean	I traded my timeshare week for a stay here, and I was very happy with the property. It's new, clean, safe, and relatively quiet, located VERY close to the Strip (Planet Hollywood, Paris, Ballys, etc.). I was awakened one night by the fellow in the next room who decided to sing karoake with a bunch of girls, but other than that, I didn't hear much. I was told that construction was going on and I heard it once and saw it once, but the entire Strip is under construction right now. Be advised: there are different types of one bedrooms. Make sure you know what you're getting. My room was small with an awesome king bed, small pull-out sofa, a roomy, nice bathroom and an efficiency kitchen with a microwave, sink, small fridge, coffee maker, plates, glassware, etc. There were only two of us and we weren't in Vegas for the hotel room, but if you think four adults can stay in that size room comfortably, think again. Two adults and a child could handle it. Oh, and I never actually saw a housekeeper and didn't have housekeeping &quot;tidy up&quot; because it costs extra $. Still, if you need extra towels, shampoo, soap, all you have to do is ask. There's a downstairs Market Place store selling all types of things and yes, it's pricey, but the new Vegas isn't cheap anymore. The days of Prime Rib and Lobster for $9.99 are gone, gone, gone. There are liquor/snack stores across the street in the Miracle Mile Shops, so you can pick up things there or take the shuttle to the local grocery. The hotel staff are nice. They keep ice cold cucumber infused water in the lobby all the time. If you decide to go on a tour, SweetTours offers several. We took one to the Grand Canyon ($130 each). It took 7 hours to get out there because of the stops (Hoover Dam, Route 66, getting gas, etc.) and 5 hours to get back. We were at the canyon for almost three hours. Worth it? Yes, especially if you have the time and don't want to pay $4.33 a gallon and drive almost 600 miles in a day. Actually, the tour was a nice break from the Strip. The pool on the 38th floor was small but well maintained. One gripe: no full-length mirrors anywhere. I &quot;complained&quot; and the concierge said &quot;that's the most common complaint we get here...&quot; (uh, then buy some?). Taxis are easy to get but walk as much as you can. The Strip's traffic jams force long wait times and a trip from the hotel down to the Mirage was $12.	
Jun 14 2008 	Well located	I recently returned from a four night stay at the Marriott Grand Chateau and must say that both my travelling companions and I were all very satisfied with our stay at the hotel. The greatest asset of the property is its central location close to the strip. Although it is not directly on Las Vegas Blvd, it is a minute from the strip right next to Planet Hollywood and the Miracle Mile shops. The hotel is new and very well maintained. Although they are presently adding another wing to the hotel, we were never disturbed by the construction noise nor from the construction noise of the other properties going up around the hotel.We booked a two bedroom penthouse suite which consited of two closed bedrooms each with its own washroom, as well as a living room with a large flat screen tv and a large kitchen fully equiped (toaster, coffee machine, glasses, plates, etc) and also included granite counter tops and a washer and dryer. The hotel also provided us with soap and laundry detergent during our stay. As usual within the Marriott chain hotels, the beds were very comfortable and also had quality linens. It is also important to mention that this hotel is a timeshare hotel so if you wish to have someone come clean your room daily, it is for an extra fee.The hotel also has a rooftop pool and bar. The views are wonderful at night. The area is kept very clean and has lounge chairs for sunbathing. Although the pool is quite small, especially when you see the pool areas of the much larger gaming hotels on the strip, it still provides a nice refreshment from the dry heat. There is a convenience store in the lobby which sells coffee, toast, sodas, juices, etc which you can purchase and prepare breakfast in your room. However, located right across the street within the Miracle Mile shops are various restaurants offering breakfast for under $5.00. There is also a Walgreens close to the hotel where you can pick up other items such as water, chips, chocolate, etc for less than the convenience store directly in the hotel.I would strongly recommend the Marriott Grand Chateau to anyone looking for a very clean, quite, safe and well located hotel close to the strip. However, if you are seeking the lights, commotion and casino ambience of the more traditional Las Vegas hotels, then it would be better to reserve at another hotel located directly on Las Vegas Blvd such as the Bellagio, MGM or Treasure Island which offer various dining options, shops, shows and casinos under the same roof.	
