May 30 2008 	Great Suite great place nice people.	We stayed here as a promotional gift to attend a Timeshare Presentation. Usually, if you're here for this reason, be prepared to not get a suite, you will likely have an intermediate room (aka &quot;Lock Off&quot; room) which is the second bedroom part of a 2 bedroom suite. As luck would have it, we happened to get the other side, a full 1 bedroom suite.The 1 bedroom suites are very nice. Not that I stay in a lot of luxury places, but I was very impressed. The room was comfortable in all ways. Being not attached to a casino, they're not trying to get you out of the room, so they have nice freebies not un-common in most cities, but not usually seen in Vegas hotels, such as free premium channels (such as HBO) and free WiFi. The Big Plasma screen was nice (the channel guide didn't work though) as well as the mini-stereo. The double shower was nice as well as the big soaking tub (was odd draining though, which could be the plumbing issues other people have mentioned.) The place was quiet, we didn't hear any construction or plumbing noise, but the AC was a bit noisy, no less than the AC units in other &quot;mainstream&quot; hotels though. As much as it was nice to have the kitchen, and as much as we planned on using it, we just didn't, but it was nice to have the option. We did use the fridge, it worked (shrug.) The pillows on the bed were a bit flat, but the front desk sent up a replacement (although we found out there were more in the closet for the pull out bed.) It was also nice to have the extra blankets in the closet since the comforter on the bed was thick and hot, the thinner blanket was perfect.We were on the 7th floor, facing the strip. No view to speak of, we could see the MGM sign, the Polo Club, construction, and part of the Belagio sign. At night though the construction view wasn't as bad, just twinkling lights and purple neon from the Polo Club. Short elevator ride though. From the roof pool though, that was a nice view. The weather was not so great (may 21st to 24th) when we were there, so the pool was closed the first day due to wind, which is probably the main down-side to a roof pool, but other things were closed in the area as well (Belagio fountains, Sirens of TI.)The lobby and exterior were nice; the mini-store was handy, although a bit expensive, but you pay for convenience. Von's (general supermarket) wasn't that far away if you have a car, we passed by it on the way to the Pinball Museum on Tropicana. There is no self parking, the Valet is the only thing to park on site, but they are fast and plenty courteous (they lost someone's keys while we were there, but took care of them well by paying for the locksmith and taxi's while they searched the area and videos to find the keys.)If you're going for a Timeshare presentation, be prepared for the presentation. I've been to a few and this one is on the nice side, but it's still sales. Plan on at least 2 hours, closer to 2.5 when you include waiting for them. The sales person we had was very personable and easy to talk to; they'll show you lots of options. (We didn't buy, but it looks like a decent deal, choose for yourself.)Checkout is a bit early for us at 10AM (well, early when you're in Vegas) but you may be able to get a late checkout, call early to find out or check the night before, they didn't have any available at 8:3AM when we called.This is a great location, fine with a car or not. We didn't have our car the first day, PH was right next door, simply across the street. It'll be even nicer when the City Center is done and when the other 2 towers are finished (another pool, larger, on top of the garage is planned.)	
