Feb 11 2008 	Excellent timeshare and rental in Las Vegas	Marriott property booked through Interval International timeshare. Construction will continue for several years according to info. provided by our time share company. Two bedroom unit not available when we wanted to travel. This review is for the One bedroom unit we booked with king size bed and sleeper sofa in living room. One bath. Furniture and bedding very good quality- comfortable except for pillows, which are standard hotel issue. We are in our early sixties and the bed provided excellent support for our arthritic backs. If you can't live without your own pillow and don't want to carry it or ship it from home, there are Brookstone and Sharper Image stores that will be glad to sell you a Tempurpedic or similar type pillow which you can ship home when you leave! Bathroom was a good size with two entry doors(one from master bedroom and one from living room if you have someone sleeping on the sleeper sofa) and had large walk-in shower with two shower heads. Jacuzzi type tub in master bedroom. Second sink and vanity area in area across from Jacuzzi with mirror/vanity and seat. Hair dryer provided. Kitchen has full size refrigerator/freezer and cooktop range, microwave,toaster,coffeemaker, blender and dinnerware.Small dishwasher. Glass round table in dining alcove seats 6. Sundry store off lobby has beverages and food items. Walgreens and CVS are about a ten minute walk.Resort has a shuttle to a Von's grocery store a few days a week (make reservations). Miracle Mile shopping mall across the street with many stores and restaurants attached to Planet Hollywood resort. Construction noise was mentioned in many of the reviews we read but we did not hear much noise in our room, which faced Las Vegas Blvd. on 21st floor. We walked to many resorts or took a cab. Bellagio, MGM, Paris,New York,NY easy walk from building. We saw several shows: &quot;O&quot; was our favorite along with another Cirque du Soliel production called &quot;Ka&quot; and a traditional Las Vegas show girl production called &quot;Jubilee&quot;. Also enjoyed walking around in Venetian, but take a cab and save your feet. Bring some Dr. Scholl's moleskin or foot padding if you are prone to blisters.There is a monorail that has stops at several hotels (MGM is closest to Marriott Grand Chateau) Monorail fare higher than cab for 2 people if you visit several properties in a day (about $5.00 per person or a bit cheaper for a 3-day pass). The cab takes you where you want to go without walking from monorail stop. A double-decker bus called &quot;the Deuce&quot; is cheaper than either monorail or cab if you don't mind the wait. No casino or restaurant in Grand Chateau, but the strip is only a block away. The kitchen comes in handy for days when your feet hurt too much to hike any further. There is a nice bar on the top floor with great view and also a health club in the building. Concierge was friendly. Only two complaints: the very loud forced air heating/cooling unit which rattles and cannot be silenced unless it is turned off (maintenance adjusted the unit but apparently this is a building-wide problem that persists). Windows do not open but if you slide the vent at the bottom of the windows, some fresh air can be felt coming in. I would not want to stay in this hotel in the extreme heat of a Las Vegas summer unless I wore ear plugs to cover the noise of the air conditioner to sleep or used an I-POD with good noise attenuating head set. If you don't mind loud air handlers or forced air units, this might not be a problem for you. The washer/dryer combo is stacked in a very small closet and both are extremely limited in size. Two shirts and some socks washed in one load but the dryer left the clothing only damp after 2 hours (very loud, also). We hung our clothes around the unit to dry over night. Laundry valet service is available. No daily maid service, which is typical in most timeshares, but you can get fresh towels daily. Don't even think about washing your own towels in the washer/dryer. Very small safe inside bedroom closet (will hold small laptop computer standing vertically). Combination lock. Wireless internet service available and business center also has computers. Entire building is non-smoking, which was great. Staff very helpful. Would stay again in winter season or early spring. Flat screen TV in living and bedroom. DVD player in living room. Since flat screen TV in living rooms of most newer hotels hang on walls, we have found that we can hear TV from next unit through wall; however, the bedroom was quiet. There is so much construction going on in Las Vegas that it will be years before it is all completed. Still-this is a town to enjoy the many things to do, good food, shows and variety of shopping. It is never boring. We slept well and the Las Vegas winters are a break from the snow and cold of the northeast U.S. The airport is a short ride from the strip and &quot;people watching&quot; is a blast here. The photos provided on most travel sites and by the Marriott are accurate.	
Feb 3 2008 	Would definitely go back	My parents own a Marriott timeshare in another location, which I exchanged for the Grand Chateau. Usually my husband and I stay at the Bellagio, and I was expecting a downgrade. However, I was very pleasantly surprised. The rooms (1 bedroom, living room with sofabed, full kitchen) were immaculate. The kitchen was very well stocked in terms of appliances, paper towels, soap, etc. The two-headed shower was a great touch, as was the tub in the bedroom big enough for two. The flat-panel TVs were also a plus. The location was great; less than five minutes to get to Planet Hollywood, about ten minutes to the Bellagio. The only downsides are that 1) the convenience store is WAY overpriced; and 2) they charge exorbitant fees for maid service, so we passed. Note: We managed to dodge the timeshare presentation, but be warned; Marriott timeshare folks are right there with the rest of them in the malls (although they're less pushy than the average timeshare folk!). All in all, a very nice experience (especially since it was free), and not too much of a step down from the Bellagio.	
Feb 2 2008 	Las Vegas View	We just returned from a week at our timeshare at the Marriott Grand Chateau in Las Vegas. January was a little too cold for us but we managed to use the wonderful hot tub on the top floor of the hotel every day. The view is magnificent and so worth a trip up to see. There is also a heated pool and a bar up there as well. There is a Market Place for necessary items such as milk, bread, cereal, sodas, snacks. There is also hot coffee and a beverage fountain in the Market Place. There is an owner's lounge that came in handy when we had to check out and our flight did not leave for a couple of hours. There are couches and a nice TV as well as computers you can use for $ .35 per minute. The staff is very helpful and courteous. We stayed in our lock off room which had refrig,coffee,toaster,microwave, dishes and silverware. The only downfall or may be a good thing is that there is no casino in the hotel, however you have Planet Hollywood and MGM right next door within walking distance. The other casino's depending on the weather are also within walking distance. We would definitely recommend this hotel especially if you are staying for a week or longer.	
Jan 21 2008 	Under Development but a Great Place to Stay	My wife and I spent a week at the Marriott Grand Chateau in mid January 2008. Although we enjoy Las Vegas, we do not smoke or gamble, and therefore, this was a great place for us. This is a time share property, not a hotel, so you can expect what a time share, particularly a Marriott time share offers, i.e., a non-smoking facility, no casino, a family friendly environment (e.g., iced water with lemon or orange always available in the lobby, cookies in the afternoon, MAZE kids club on site, etc.). The rooms are large and well appointed; we enjoyed watching the sunsets from our room as the lights came up on the city. Also, the living room featured a 42&quot; LCD television with 95 channels and a DVD player. The place is new and in some areas still under construction, so it looks great, and it is very clean and nice. But don't expect daily maid service unless you want to pay extra, and don't expect many of the usual hotel features, like a spa or restaurants, as neither are on site. But, you do get complimentary valet parking that is fast, friendly and efficient, and the location, 1 block off the Strip across the street from Planet Hollywood, and 2 blocks from the Bellagio, is great. There is a workout facility on site, a roof-top pool and hot tub (we did not use them as it was cold and windy while we were there, but the view from the roof, 37 stories above the desert, is not to be missed), and a roof top bar that is open during the warm months. And, with a friendly and efficient staff that takes care of your needs consistent with the location (i.e., concierge service is available on site, but room service is not), this is a great place to stay in Vegas.	
Jan 16 2008 	Excellent Stay - I will return!	First off, the Hotel is brand new and located about 200 yards from the Strip (Las Vegas Boulevard). I have stayed at many great hotels in Las Vegas before and this place was great. The service was top notch with friendly personnel at the front desk/valet/belldesk, etc... The Lobby is very clean and smoke free with NO casino! This was a bonus since you do need some down time from all the noise and excitement of the Strip. Valet parking is also free.The room was huge. I had a Villa Suite. It was perfect and very clean. Plasma TV on the wall in the family room, a large kitchen with all the cabinets stocked, a full size fridge, oven, stove, microwave, double headed shower, and a sink and massive bathtub in the bed area. I had a guest that slept on the sofa which converted into a bed. He said it was one of the best nights sleep he had ever had. He could not believe that a sofa bed could be so comfortable, and I tried it and it was quite nice. The King size bed in the main room was also very comfortable and also included its own TV. Both rooms also had DVD players and you can rent movies down in the Lobby. They did a great job cleaning the rooms and even made up the sofa bed after the first night of using it.My favorite thing to do at Hotels is to use the fitness center and pool area. Let me tell you about the fitness center. It had all the equipment you could ever need and it was very clean. Plenty of TVs to watch on the treadmills and other equipment. The best part was the Locker room which included a huge steam room. I have never been in a steam room that was as efficient as this one. You could hardly see your hand if front of your face. It was magnificient!To top it off (no pun intended) , the Hotel decided to put a Pool, Hot Tub and Bar on the top of the Hotel. It was January, so I did not see anyone using the Heated Pool or Hottub. Well, I had a few friends join me at the pool. We enjoyed the Hot Tub for about an hour. It was so nice. Not one person bothered us because they were not there (and the hotel was completely booked!). The view was amazing. You could see the whole Strip from end to end. There were heating lamps out on a patio in front of the bar to keep you warm and smoking was allowed in a small area. The bar was closed because it was winter, but in the summer time it will be perfect.I really enjoyed myself at this hotel and I plan on staying here every year when I return for the Consumer Electronics Show in January.Regarding the construction going on at nearby properties and at the Marriott property, I did not hear a single thing realted to construction. In fact I could not hear anything outside at all. The room is sealed very well. Keep in mind my room was facing the strip. If you face the opposite direction (towards the airport) you may hear something but I can not attest to that. I only have one complaint and this is because I am a technology enthusiast. They have beautiful HD Sony Plasma TV's in every room, however they are only delivering analog programming to every room. This blows me away. What a waste of a TV. There is no reason to have these TV's if they are not going to deliver High Definition content. In fact, this is not dificult to do either and would cost the hotel $0 since all the local TV stations broadcast Over the Air (received with an antenna) in High Definition and is FREE. If anyone from the hotel reads this review, please make an upgrade to the TV service.IOther than my one issue with the TVs I HIGHLY recommend staying here. You will be treated nicely and will enjoy your stay.	
Jan 15 2008 	Awesome first time in Vegas	It was my first time to Vegas and my husband's first time back in 20 years. My first glimpse of The Strip was overwhelming. Huge hotels and billions of $$ represented. We arrived on the Saturday after Thanksgiving and only had to go 3/4 mile down the strip to turn onto Harmon Street to reach the Marriott's Grand Chateau. It took us almost an hour! The foot traffic and auto traffic was unbelievable. It took us 20 minutes just to go 7 car spaces to turn onto Harmon Street. We then decided that we would avoid driving on the Strip when we went out driving. We soon learnt the back roads that run parellel with the Strip. We arrived at the Grand Chateau and first impressions were awesome! They had valet and bell hops there to assist with your luggage. Valet was complimentary - great bonus! Check in was a breeze and then it was up to our suite. We were on the 31st floor and the elevator ride was very quick and ear popping! Our suite was beautiful. We had an awesome view of the mountains in the distance. We did overlook the construction going on across the road at Planet Hollywood but it did not obstruct our view of the mountains. We also had a slight view of one part of the strip too. So plenty to see out the window.After unpacking we then went down to the lobby to see if we could get show tickets. We went to the conceirge and she was fabulous. One show I have been wanting to see was Danny Gans. When we tried to get tickets before our trip we couldn't as it was sold out. But our conceirge got us on the aisle seats for Wednesday evening. Unfortunately she couldn't get us Celine Dion tickets as well but that's the way some of the shows go. We were also able to get tickets to Mamma Mia! for Thursday night. Both shows were excellent and we had excellent seats for the shows. Our suite was very well appointed with a full kitchen, dining area, living room, bedroom, huge two person soaking tub, seperate shower and washer and dryer. Everything was beautifully doecorated. In fact out of all the MVCI's I have stayed at this was the nicest. My only complaint about the suite was the washer and dryer were very small so you couldn't wash much. One load was two of my shirts and two of my husbands. We tried drying them in the dryer but after three hours we gave up and hung them up on hangers to dry.One thing I did like is that they offered a free shuttle service once a day to the local supermarket so you could buy items to prepare in your suite. That is much better than buying food from the Marketplace in the lobby. The prices in the marketplace were a bit on the high side.We went up to the roof top bar/pool area to get some great shots of the full moon rising above the mountains. The area was very small. The pool area was tiny. For families there is not much around the pool area for the kids to do. The pool is about 3-4ft deep and about 20 feet long. They had a spa pool there too which holds about 4-6 adults The bar area was outdoors and the only area in the entire hotel where you can smoke. Being a non-smoker I love the fact that Marriott has 100% smoke-free in all their hotel rooms. But trying to enjoy the fabulous view from the roof top with smokers around was difficult. It will be interesting to see if they do anything else with the rooftop area once the other three towers are fully completed.One thing I will say though, we were there for a week and not once were we disturbed by the construction in the second tower. There was the inconvenience of having to open fire doors while they did silent alarm tests, but that was only minor. As far as construction goes our complaint was with Planet Hollywood who seemed to be working 24/7 on their site across the road. The only time we were disturbed by the their construction was when they were pumping concrete from the ground floor to the 18th floor at 3am! Those pumps were very loud!Over all we had a fabulous stay at the MVCI Grand Chateau and would not hesitate to get back there again. You are only 1/2 block from the stirp, which made it convenient to get to the strip. The MVCI doesn't have any restaurants but they are within walking distance of several eating places. We either brought stuff to prepare at the local supermarket or we would eat whereever we were.Overall my first experience in Vegas was great. I would love to go back again and explore some more. If I can stay at the MVCI Grand Chateau again I would not complain! I have no idea what they charge for a room rate at the Grand Chateau. We traded a week at another MVCI for a week at the Grand Chateau. I know you can rent the rooms but I don't know what they would go for.	
